snippet.textDisplay:
Do you want to know what else I have to say that is as absurd as Alex's summaries of these bad Riverdale episodes? February 13, 2020, 1:05am



I am creating an animated film that will break the mold of the Animation genre, to show people what animation can do and remind people how animation can be a genre for adults, without being too ugly or violent. It is called Plush! Plush is a subverted kids film, that I never meant to be for kids at all because it is actually meant for 20-something parents with little children. Plush is an animated film starring Ashleigh Ball, Gabriel C. Brown, Eric McCormack, and Kimiko Glenn. They all play kids who are very close friends with their plush animals. They go on fun, imaginary adventures with the plush animals, but they also move around with the plush toys in their underwear. Plush has a lot of good social commentary about why it is good to let kids play with stuffed animals in private, and how that will give them a healthy perspective on sex when they are older. When the kids try to make real, non-plush friends, one of them turns out to be an evil banana who gets them sent to a juvenile correctional facility where they get their pleasure centers removed. You might think it is illegal to show children with toys in their underwear, even if they are still fully-clothed otherwise, since it is bad to show any children in sexual situations (Jodie Foster needed her older sister to stand in for her in Taxi Driver when she was 13) but maybe if it's animated, we can get away with it, right?
